            "content": "CIPP pipe lining works for most sewer pipe damage but has limitations with completely collapsed sections. If the pipe has collapsed to the point where we cannot navigate a camera through the damaged section or insert the liner, we may need to use pipe bursting instead of lining. Pipe bursting is still a trenchless method—it fractures and displaces the old pipe while pulling new HDPE pipe into place, requiring only small access pits rather than continuous trenching. For partial collapses where camera access remains possible, CIPP lining often works excellently—the pressurized liner expands to fill the damaged area and restores the pipe to full diameter. During our initial camera inspection, we determine whether standard CIPP lining is suitable or if pipe bursting or spot excavation is necessary. In many cases, we can use CIPP lining for most of your sewer line and pipe bursting or limited excavation for severely collapsed sections, giving you the benefits of trenchless technology for the majority of your repair while addressing extreme damage with minimal excavation."
